When executing the same query second time, the query runs faster. The file system cache holds data that was recently read from the disk, making it possible for subsequent requests to obtain data from cache rather than having to read it again from the disk. Because memory access is many times faster than disk access, leaving some physical memory available for the file system cache can boost performance.

After Clear filesystem cache on both the worker nodes using `echo 3 | sudo tee /proc/sys/vm/drop_caches` and again executing the count query takes 27 seconds in comparison to 19 seconds when data is present in the filesystem cache.

%md
Both the approaches generates same outputs for number of rows i.e. 21759408. Both approaches nearly takes same amount of time. In this case, after clearing filesystem cache, bash command execution of 1.8GB of data took 22 seconds and hive query took 27 seconds.
Probable reason would be Hive needs to get data from HDFS and as overheads was launching map and reduce tasks in order to run query on it. Whereas in case of bash, data is already copied to local directory. However, in general, Bash is slower than Hive, especially when dealing with large file like 7GB-1TB.

SELECT indicatorValue AS GDP_growth_value, year, countryName
FROM (SELECT indicatorValue, year, countryName
           ,DENSE_RANK() OVER (PARTITION BY countryName ORDER BY indicatorValue DESC, year DESC) AS con_max_gdp
      FROM wdi_csv_parquet
       WHERE indicatorCode="NY.GDP.MKTP.KD.ZG") AS Gdp
WHERE con_max_gdp=1
